Assignment 10 Reflection

Introduction

This assignment focused on transforming a UML Class Diagram into working code while applying creational design patterns and validating the implementation through unit testing.

Challenges Faced

1. Translating UML to Code

One challenge was converting abstract class diagrams into concrete implementations. Deciding how to represent relationships such as associations and responsibilities required careful consideration.

2. Applying Creational Patterns

Understanding when and where to apply each creational pattern was not straightforward. For example:

Builder was used for flexible object construction
Singleton required careful handling to ensure only one instance exists
Abstract Factory required structuring related object creation

3. Project Structure and Imports

Managing Python imports and folder structure caused initial issues, especially when running tests with pytest. Fixing module paths and ensuring correct package structure was necessary.


Alignment with Previous Assignments

This assignment builds directly on earlier work:
Assignment 3: System architecture guided module structure
Assignment 4: Functional requirements influenced class methods
Assignment 5: Use cases were implemented as system behaviors
Assignment 6: User stories translated into features
Assignment 7: Tasks implemented through GitHub workflow
Assignment 8 & 9: Class diagrams became actual code

Design Decisions

Python was chosen for simplicity and readability
Creational patterns were used to improve flexibility and scalability
Code was modularized into separate folders for clarity
Unit testing ensured correctness and reliability

Lessons Learned

Design patterns are useful for managing complexity in larger systems
Proper project structure is critical for testing and maintainability
Translating diagrams into code requires both technical and conceptual understanding
Testing is essential to validate assumptions made during design

Conclusion

This assignment successfully bridges the gap between system design and implementation. It demonstrates how theoretical models such as UML diagrams and design patterns can be applied to build a working, testable system.
